**me:** ok so i built this rate limiter with 3 token buckets — per second, per minute, per hour. each request has to acquire from all 3 before it can proceed. but im worried about something. if thread A grabs the per_second bucket and then before it grabs per_minute, thread B also grabs per_second... is that a problem? like is there a deadlock risk here

**AI:** No deadlock risk. The reason is actually pretty simple — you're acquiring all three locks in the same fixed order every time. per_second → per_minute → per_hour, always. Deadlock needs a circular wait to happen. Thread A holds per_second, wants per_minute. Thread B would need to hold per_minute and want per_second for a cycle. But Thread B can't even reach per_minute without first going through per_second — which Thread A holds. So the cycle is impossible.

The scenario you described — Thread A grabs per_second, Thread B also grabs per_second before A reaches per_minute — that's fine. Each bucket enforces its own limit independently. The composite limiter's guarantee is just that by the time any request finishes all three acquisitions, the rates are within bounds. Doesn't need to be atomic across all three simultaneously.

